{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ba3c0555-215e-478b-902d-09864507ed99","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **abstract file I/O behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen inject `IFileSystem` into your classes instead of calling `System.IO` directly. In production, wire up a real implementation; in tests, use a mock/fake.\n\n**Alternatively**, use the [`System.IO.Abstractions`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions) NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` out of the box plus a `MockFileSystem` for testing:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```\n\n```csharp\n// Production\nservices.AddSingleton<IFileSystem>(new FileSystem());\n\n// Tests\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>\n{\n    { \"/data/config.json\", new MockFileData(\"{ }\") }\n});\nvar sut = new MyService(fs);\n```\n\nThis avoids rolling your own abstraction and covers the full `System.IO` surface.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"72b080ff-3497-4537-9b86-b750d60ed1e8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in .NET. This is a design/architecture question about dependency injection and abstraction of file system calls. I don't need to explore the codebase for this - it's a general best practices question.\n\nLet me give a concise answer about the standard approaches.","outputTokens":394,"requestId":"0423:C1158:21CD80D:261415E:69E8282B"},"id":"f95bec2c-4dba-42f5-8656-b3de6377ea47","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:45:25.574Z","parentId":"c1a3b332-b53f-4bfa-a25d-5a0726513f3c"}
